\strong{The combiner (transparent, no model).} Each index contributes one
per-respondent flag (\verb{$flags}, a respondent x index table, \code{NA} where the index
abstains). Correlated indices then \strong{collapse to one vote}: indices that share
a registry \code{vote_group} fuse into a single vote that fires when \strong{any} member
flagged the respondent (an abstaining member counts as not flagged). Only
even-odd and personal reliability share a group (\code{consistency}) -- they measure
one construct, so weighting them as two votes would double-count. The collapsed
votes are in \verb{$votes}; the count of flagged constructs per respondent is
\code{rowSums(votes)}.

\strong{Agreement, not a per-index rate.} Because an empirical-percentile cutoff
flags its target rate by construction, a per-index flag rate is tautological.
\verb{$agreement} (from the internal cross-index agreement diagnostic) instead
reports, for each level k, the
observed share of respondents flagged by at least k votes against the share
expected if the votes fired independently; observed far above expected makes a
clustered careless subgroup visible. In the printed table the \verb{<- excess}
marker appears only where the observed count would be unlikely under vote
independence (a one-sided binomial tail below 0.05) -- a descriptive guard so
ordinary sampling noise is not advertised as contamination, not a formal
test. The Mahalanobis chi-square and Gnormed
Monte-Carlo votes carry their calibrated null nominal (the rest are
percentile, hence \code{NA}).

\strong{Interpreting and reporting.} The percentile cutoff is a \strong{ranking
convention}, not a calibrated false-positive rate: it cuts a tail of the size
you choose (\code{fpr}) and flags about that share of \emph{this} sample by construction.
It is \strong{not} Goldammer et al.'s simulated-null Sen95 operating point and makes
no claim about the true false-positive rate. Treat the exclusion as a
researcher decision: \strong{report results before and after} removing flagged
respondents, and show the flag rate across \code{fpr} (for example 0.01, 0.05, 0.10)
so readers can see its sensitivity to a threshold you set. \code{vignette("cier")}
walks through this.
